Yes — if you take proper backups first, you can recover from operator issues much more safely.

But there are two very different things here:

1. Backup of Kubernetes/ODF configuration

This helps restore:

Subscriptions

StorageCluster CR

CephCluster CR

ODF configs


But NOT actual PVC application data.

Example backup:

mkdir -p /root/odf-backup

oc get storagecluster -n openshift-storage ocs-storagecluster -o yaml > /root/odf-backup/storagecluster.yaml

oc get cephcluster -n openshift-storage -o yaml > /root/odf-backup/cephcluster.yaml

oc get sub,csv,installplan -n openshift-storage -o yaml > /root/odf-backup/operators.yaml

oc get sc -o yaml > /root/odf-backup/storageclasses.yaml

2. Actual application/PVC data backup

This is what protects real data.

Deleting StorageCluster can destroy:

Ceph pools

RBD images

CephFS

object buckets


Configuration backup alone CANNOT recover application data if disks are wiped.

For real protection you need:

OADP/Velero

CSI snapshots

external replication

rsync/app backup

Ceph mirroring


Since your current issue is only upgrade orchestration, there is no need to take the dangerous path of deleting StorageCluster.

Safer approach:

keep Ceph running

repair OLM subscriptions

let operators reconcile


That is recoverable and low risk.

Deleting StorageCluster is high risk and unnecessary for your current situation.
